Further, in what can only be described as a drop in the bucket for Kushner's disclosure crimes, the Office of Government Ethics recently fined him $200 for filing paperwork late detailing the transfer of management for his many business interests.

Adding insult to injury, Kushner's stake in his family company remains valued at over $600 million, and the company has openly touted touts Kushner's closeness to the President as part of their pitch to foreign investors.

Of course, $200 is not punishment for Kushner and will do nothing to deter him from continuing to hide his financial strings as much as he can, but the fact that he was fined is significant in itself.
